body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Consider this dummy test, Verilog and SBY files:
```verilog
`default_nettype none
module fsm (input wire clk, rstn, start, a, b, c, d,
            output reg [1:0] state_val);
        
        localparam [3:0] s0=0, s1=1, s2=2, s3=3;
        reg [1:0] ps, ns;

        wire jump_s2, jump_s3, return_w;
        assign jump_s2 = &({a,b,c,d});
        assign jump_s3 = (~a & b & c & ~d);
        assign return_w  = (a | d & ~b);

        always @(posedge clk) begin
                if (~rstn) ps <= s0;
                else       ps <= ns;
        end
        
        always @(*) begin
                ns = ps;
                case (ps)
                        s0: if (start)   ns = s1;
                        s1: if (jump_s2) ns = s2;
                        s2: if (jump_s3) ns = s3;
                        s3: if (return_w)  ns = s0;
                endcase
        end
        assign state_val = ps;

        // Assertion logic
        always @(*) assume (rstn == 1'b1);
        always @(posedge clk) if (ps == s2 && jump_s3) assert (ps == s3);
endmodule
```
SBY:
```
[options]
mode bmc

[engines]
smtbmc boolector

[script]
read_verilog -formal fsm.v
prep -top fsm

[files]
fsm.v
```
## Expected behavior
When a formal tool finds a failure, it shows a concise CEX with logic that influences the assertion/cover logic. For this particular example the logic influences are: `ps`, `jump_s3`, `clk` and `rstn`, as shown in the following VCD. The rest of the tools also shows the exact moment where the assertion failed (see `assert_always_i` transition from 1 to 0 (falsification)).

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10665129/86168164-67c93600-badd-11ea-839c-d6e41d6af209.png)


## Actual behavior
User needs to get signals from the generated VCD file, and correlate it back with the RTL. For trivial modules it may not represent a problem. For big designs, both in size and depth (states), this kind of debuggability may represent a barrier of tool adoption. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10665129/86169394-29cd1180-badf-11ea-9abe-7cf156ae0fe9.png)

A quick workaround is to separate the formal "testbench" into separate file, `bind` or instantiate it into the top module, and when a CEX or reached cover is found, get the signals from the container, as starting point. But still requires human intervention. 

```verilog
// Assert container
module assert_always (input wire event_m, disable_e, precondition, condition);
`ifndef _SV_
	always @(*) assume (disable_e == 1'b1);
	always @(posedge event_m)
                if (precondition) assert (condition);
`else
	assert_always_i: assert property (@(posedge event_m) disable iff (!disable_e) 
					    precondition |-> condition);
`endif

// Assert container instance
wire cause  = (ps == s2 && jump_s3);
wire effect = (ps == s3); // check ns instead, to fix it
assert_always checker_inst (clk, rstn, cause, effect);
endmodule
```

Maybe a better approach is to add a mechanism in `backends/smt2/smt2.cc` to add that information in the SMT generated model, as a comment like how it extracts the assertion name, and let `smtio.py` and `smtbmc.py` deal with the extra information needed in the `generate_vcd` function.

